Fundamentally the big factors are US-China trade war and spillover to korean exports; Japan-Korea trade conflict / tariffs; coronovirus impact on SK, US and China; Bank efforts both US/SK via fiscal and monetary policy... and so foreign money outflows. Given this Won has held up vs USD quite well and the crowd forecast at writing of 42% in the 1150/1200 range seems reasonable as the most likely scenario. But the weight seems more disperse. Inflation is expected to decline in both South Korea and the US due to demand shocks from the coronavirus. South Korea is more dependent on China, so the effects may be more pronounced there. Fed cuts will increase the incentive to hold South Korean currency relative to the dollar. Although, South Korea may also cut rates in response to similar pressures. The US Current Account Balance is strengthening and the South Korean Current Account Balance is decreasing which will drive USD appreciation (i.e. more won per dollar). Further, continued concerns about global growth will increase demand for the USD to hold haven assets.
